When fspclient (fsp) is used to "grab" a file.  The local file is 
always deleted.  

The fsp grab command is designed to do an atomic get/delete on a remote
file.  The client/util/util.c(util_grab_file) routine does a correct
FSP protocol transaction and after verifying that the file has been
safely transfered, it send the "grabdone" command which tells the
server to delete the remote file.

Since the transfer was done correctly, util_grab_file() returns 0.

The routine client/remote/rgrab.c(grab_file) expects util_grab_file()
to return the number of bytes transferred correctly.  Since util_grab_file()
is returning 0 (correct transfer) and grab_file() expects byte count, the
result is grab_file() sees an incorrect file transfer and unlink()s the
bad local file.

Fix: 

While not a diff, the following shows corrected code:
       int flag;

        flag = util_grab_file(name, fd, 0, sbufp->st_size);
        (void)close(fd);

        if (flag < 0)
        {
            retval = 1;
            (void)unlink(path);
        }
        else
            dirty = 1;
    }
How-To-Repeat: 
start fsp server.
start fsp client
grab remote_file_name

note that the remote file is missing as is the local file
